So, @BobPisani $TXN was supposed to be an important "tell." The shares are now -$8 from the post EPS release high. What is the "tell" to you? I shorted the gap @realmoney and added to $MU short.

Mindless talking heads in biz media "loved" the $TXN report without even reading the release comprehensively and listening to the conference call. Same old shoddy and superficial analysis we see day in and day out. Miles long but only inches deep, Sir Fred.

I often write that coming to an investment conclusion after an EPS release without listening to the conference call and digesting the report usually leads to non optimal trading. Case in point - $TXN gave up its +$5/share post report gain and is now lower based on cautionary
comments.

@realdonaldtrump There’s a Bigger Prize Than Impeachment nyti.ms/2W0iAtJ A powerful argument against impeachment. Excerpt: For Democrats, leaving Donald Trump in office is not only good politics — it is the best chance for fundamental realignment of American politics in

more than a generation. Mr. Trump is three years into destroying what we know as the Republican Party. Another two years just might finish it off. Trumpism has become Republicanism, and that spells electoral doom for the party. Mr. Trump has abandoned most of the core principles

that have defined Republicans for the past century. Free trade abandoned for protectionism. Challenging our adversaries and promoting democracy replaced by coddling Russia and cozying up to dictators near and far. Fiscal conservatism replaced by reckless spending and exploding

deficits. What’s left of the party is a rigid adherence to tax cuts, a social agenda that repels most younger Americans and rampant xenophobia and race-based politics that regularly interfere with the basic functioning of the federal government.

washingtonpost.com/opinions/… @realdonaldtrump In short, Giuliani acknowledges that Trump, just as Mueller said in the report, eagerly looked to Russia to help win the presidency. If Trump really cannot acknowledge that such conduct is a betrayal of our sovereign country, he has

no business being its president. It’s ironic for a president who was obsessed with Democrats’ trying to delegitimize his presidency to defend himself by acknowledging he looked to Russian hackers to win the election.

The administration is trapped in its own spin. Having claimed vindication by the report, Trump and his flunkies now must deny what is in it, avoid answering questions for which there is no good answer and/or deny that getting help from a hostile power betrays our country.

That might get the administration through a news cycle or two, but at some point a significant majority of Americans may conclude Trump is a menace to our Constitution — to our sovereignty — and must be ejected before he can do more harm.

@realmoney In The Good Old Days In "The Good Old Days" we would look at my Key Observations column (from late yesterday afternoon) and surmise that lower volume, weakening breadth, poor small cap stock performance, higher crude prices, indicators of renewed speculative activity

and narrowing market leadership as possible signposts of weakness in the days to come: But these are not "The Good Old Days." Rather this continues to be a market dominated by central bank interference and by a changed market structure in which machines/algos and products and

strategies that worship at the altar of price momentum and are agnostic to the concept of value or "margin of safety." Stated simply, natural price discovery and some of the old rules no longer apply - and those that have been weaned, experienced and have been taught to respect
that history have been, to some degree, left out in the cold... For now. @jimcramer @tomkeene @TeamCavuto @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @michaelsantoli @carlquintanilla
